[[File:RCA from hyde park.JPG|thumb|The [[Royal College of Art]], location of the 20/21 British Art Fair until 2015.]]
The '''20/21 British Art Fair''' is a [[London]]-based art fair presenting modern, post [[World War II|War]] and contemporary [[British art]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/art/artsales/8758403/2021-British-Art-Fair-No-holding-back-Modern-Britain.html | title=20/21 British Art Fair: No holding back Modern Britain | date=12 September 2011 | first=Colin | last=Gleadell | newspaper=[[Daily Telegraph]] }}</ref>
A number of galleries exhibit at the fair each year.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.englandgallery.com/2021-british-art-fair/ | title=England & Co, Stand 23, 20/21 British Art Fair, 11–16 September 2007, The Royal College of Art, London SW7 | accessdate=22 December 2016 | publisher=England & Co. Gallery | date=2007 | location=UK }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.alanwheatleyart.com/art-fairs/18/20-21-British-Art-Fair-2015/ | title=20/21 British Art Fair, 2015 | accessdate=22 December 2016 | publisher=Alan Wheatley Art | date=2015 | location=UK }}</ref> The fair has been held at the [[Royal College of Art]] in [[South Kensington]], west London, in September each year.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.rca.ac.uk/news-and-events/events/2021-british-art-fair/ | title=20/21 British Art Fair | accessdate=22 December 2016 | publisher=[[Royal College of Art]] | location=UK }}</ref> In 2012, the fair celebrated its 25th anniversary.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://britishartfair.co.uk/25th-anniversary/ | title=25th Anniversary | accessdate=22 December 2016 | publisher=20/21 British Art Fair | date=2012 | location=UK }}</ref> Due to a loss of availability of the venue, it was cancelled in 2016, but in June 2017 it was held during at the [[Mall Galleries]] in [[St James's]], central London.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.antiquestradegazette.com/news/2016/2021-british-art-fair-to-be-relaunched-at-new-venue-in-june-2017/ | title=20/21 British Art Fair to be relaunched at new venue in June 2017 | date=30 March 2016 | first=Anna | last=Brady | work=Antiques Trade Gazette }}</ref> In 2018, the exhibit moved to [[Saatchi Gallery]] at the [[Duke of York's Headquarters|Duke of York's HQ]], which is intended to become the exhibit's new permanent home.<ref>[https://www.britishartfair.co.uk/history/ British Art Fair History.]</ref>
